{
  "project": "fixture-shop",
  "title": "Webhook Signature Verification with HMAC-SHA256",
  "slug": "webhook-hmac-signature-verification",
  "date": "2026-07-17",
  "depth": "intro",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "name": "HMAC Signature Verification",
      "definition": "A security technique where a recipient recomputes a keyed hash (HMAC) over a message using a shared secret and compares it against a signature supplied by the sender, confirming the message is authentic and untampered."
    },
    {
      "name": "Constant-Time Comparison",
      "definition": "A string comparison method that always takes the same amount of time regardless of how many characters match, preventing attackers from inferring the correct value by measuring how long comparisons take (a timing side-channel attack)."
    }
  ],
  "files": ["src/verify.php"],
  "commit": "da97ed4",
  "sources": [],
  "lesson": "The `verify()` function in `src/verify.php` decides whether an incoming webhook really came from the payment gateway. It recomputes an HMAC-SHA256 signature over the raw request payload using the shared secret — this is [[fixture-shop/_glossary#HMAC Signature Verification|HMAC signature verification]] — then compares that against the signature header the sender provided. The comparison uses PHP's `hash_equals()`, a [[fixture-shop/_glossary#Constant-Time Comparison|constant-time comparison]], so an attacker cannot learn the correct signature byte by byte from response timing."
}

